Tyler Perry is an amazing man he knows how to act, direct and produce. This movie was by far the funniest Madea yet! Tyler Perry defiantly knows how to put actors together that can make you laugh for the entire movie.

Tyler Perry is a very interesting person. He gives Tommy Wiseau a run for his money. In pretty much all his movies, there is random sub-plot drama that I love to make fun of. There is always some woman in an abusive relationship or trying to better herself, up to a family member slowly dying from a disease. Personally, I just wish he'd stick directly on the Madea character. She's the main star that everyone wants to see. That's what was great about her last outing, Witness Protection. It was basically focused on her and dealing with Eugene Levy's family.

A Madea Christmas kinda returns to the basics with a little family drama, but not overkill. It was the right amount of drama and the right amount of Madea. It's filled with good comedy, cheesy but funny one- liners, good messages, and should hopefully put you in the Christmas spirit.

Madea is working part-time at a department store for the holidays with her friend, Eileen. Eileen is depressed because her daughter, Lacey won't be able to make it home for Christmas. Eileen asks a reluctant Madea to help drive her out to Alabama to Lacey's for Christmas. Lacey is startled because she has not told her mom that she has married a white man named Conner. Lacey soon has to deal with in-laws, keeping secrets from her mom and trying to get the Christmas Jubilee to keep its religious tone. If you love Madea and Christmas movies, I highly recommend A MADEA CHRISTMAS!!!

I recommend this to every Madea/Tyler Perry fan and even to people that's never seen a Madea/Tyler Perry film. It was absolutely the most hilarious film I've seen this year besides "We're the Millers" and the funniest in the Madea series. I'm a big Madea/Tyler Perry fan and it made me laugh till I was in tears, it touched my heart in certain scenes and I can relate to each character in the film. The story was superb, the acting was great and it's a great feel good film. Tyler Perry hit it out of the ball park once again as Madea and I can't wait for his future projects ahead! I HIGHLY recommend everyone to go see it even if it's after Christmas! Great job once again and God bless to you Tyler Perry. Can't wait to buy it on DVD to add to my collection!

After spending the early afternoon engrossed in Parton's seminal work, A Smokey Mountain Christmas, my partner and I decided to travel further down the rabbit hole of Christmas movies and stumbled upon, quite by accident, this masterpiece of cinema.  Like Fellini's 8 1/2, I was never quite sure if the events in the movie were set in the real world or in some parallel dimension where things are just slightly off.  This is even more obvious with Madea herself who has the gift of evoking a kind of waking dream quite spontaneously as if it were taking place rightoutside her own consciousness.  Why did a poinsettia farmer have so much influence with the mayor who apparently had the authority to fire a school teacher and why was the school seemingly in the same building with the courthouse?  It may have been enough to flip gender and race, but when vehicles flipped without warning, it was a brilliant mess.  My only regret is that I did not have director commentary for this.

As crass and irreverent as the character Madea can be, you can easily feel the love and see the message meant to convey. Eileen learns, Bailey learns, Tanner learns. I absolutely love the chemistry that was so apparent between Larry, the cable guy and Kathy Najimi - great casting job!

For me it's more personal. Watching Eileen and her daughter is like seeing a film about my grandmother and my mother! Eileen seems like the nice one, everybody loves her, compared to her friend/relative Madea. But then it becomes clear that, while Madea cuts right to the loud, overbearing, and sometimes outright rude truth, Eileen lies  and manipulates her daughter with HER version of the truth. In the end though, she's forced to see that her daughter has her own life. Madea is impossible, Eileen is worse, and the daughter loves them all no matter what!

I think that all of the lead characters were casted correctly but some of the supporting and even minor roles definitely feel out of place and unrealistic. Granted it is fiction but the story doesn't seem believable and while I appreciate the reverse roles of racism and the dialogue it brings, the back story of them all coming together to save the town's Christmas Jubilee just doesn't seem like the most plausible story. And all in all, it just lacks the spark that some of the Madea series early stories bring. I like it for the humor of Perry and Larry the Cable Guy and for the potential of the plot but could never love it because it doesn't have the spark that should be present with Perry being such a blockbuster within movie and television.

Of all the Madea movies, this is the one that strikes just the right balance between comedy and drama. If this is your first Madea movie, I would recommend not bothering with the rest of them. The serious subjects are too serious in Madea's other movies, and the comedy scenes and quips are few and far between. This one has plenty of Madea with a subject of reverse racism that was not played too heavily at all. You know what's going to happen in the first 10 minutes, but that's not the point. You're there to laugh at Madea and shake your head at the petty bickering during the holidays. This movie became an instant Christmas classic for me, and if you can get past the other Madea movie flops, you might just enjoy this one. As for other Madea movies, others have recommended watching the plays on DVD rather than the actual movie versions. I haven't tried them yet, but I'll give one or two a chance. As for A Madea Christmas, I wish she would come see MY family for the holidays!

A Madea Christmas the Movie is classic Madea cutting up and getting everyone in order during the Christmas season. Madea gets employed at a department store and of course things do not work out. She ends up going with her niece (Ilene) to visit her great niece (Lacey) in the country on her farm. Her great niece is living their with a gentleman (Tanner) who she happens to be married. The story continues on with both sides of their (Lacey and Tanner's) families coming together. SPOILER ALERT: My family and I hollered when Madea used one of the students for Jesus on the cross. We had to pause the movie we were laughing so hard. Another favorite scene is the adventure of Madea going to visit her niece's. The entire journey is hilarious. From the KKK scene to the "Somebody has to be an activist. Somebody's got to call Sharpton" scene. Great moments!

This guy's films are always enjoyable for the gentleness of the stories and the humor.  Serious themes are explored and serious things happen, but the overall vibe retains a classic old-school American cinema quality.  The characters fit certain iconic personality types, but each has something quirky or different enough to keep them from seeming cliched or too predictable.  This has a great cast with excellent chemistry between them.  Everything feels very natural even though the story is presented in a stylized way, with a lot of events and issues taking place quickly.  I particularly liked the exploration of the issue of Christianity in Christmas celebrations and displays, a timely topic of freedom of religion and free speech in our nation.  The film in a sense uses a feather to strike a heavy blow against negating the religious ideals that many people wish to be free to make during the Christmas season.

The Super Positive: what I adore in Madea/Tyler Perry's trick bag is the changeup and total flipping of archetypes and stereotypes.

And if you ever had a frothing-at-the-mouth Killah Tiger Mom, no matter your race, ethnic heritage, you'll FREAKIN' WISH it was as easy to changeup a mean mom's decades of family torture as it is in about 70 minutes in this fun holiday film.

I've been a huge fan of Tyler Perry's work long before the world knew him.  I have been saddened by some of his movie releases that went directly word for word the lines of his play in a lot instances which didn't fit the movie screen OR the plot of the movie.  His usage of his various actors and actresses who've appeared in his numerous plays & sitcoms, I applaud him for that and then weaving in actors/actresses that we love to see on the big screen.  A Madea Christmas did not disappoint with the storyline but it did with the casting.  I felt he hit the nail on the head with most of the cast but I did not like the role of the daughter ... I'm not a big fan of Tiki Sumpter for the fact that no matter the emotion that needs to be portrayed on screen - her face never changes nor is she good at making her voice match the emotion (happy, sad etc) which to me is not effective especially when you bouncing off of Ann Marie Horsford, it's called boring.  I do give this 4 stars b/c of the overall storyline and watching Larry the Cable Guy and Madea together on screen is stomach clinching hilarious! Seeing "Blair" on screen - plus! The guy from House of Paynes in the role of lawyer - loved that guy of HOP!

A relative who loves Tyler Perry movies thought this one was his worst.  In the original teaser trailers, there are kids sitting on Madea's lap as she plays a mall Santa. None of that was in the actual movie and my relative was disappointed at being hoodwinked.  I watched it and found this is a slow moving movie and once you see what the message is, you feel like someone in charge is being overly self righteous and probably thought of the entire underlying plot while having a half a glass of wine with a single "Reason for the Season" thought/cliche recollection. A saving grace was the comedy of Larry the Cable guy especially playing the dozens with Madea.

Wow, I can't believe all the good reviews here.  Hate to say it, but this movie is a mass-market brainless waste of time.  The only reason I even saw it (I have never seen another Madea movie and am sure I never willingly will now after this) was that my son was in it as one of the schoolchildren.  Otherwise, it is a total waste of time and the best acting performance in it is given by Larry the Cable Guy (that should tell you something!).  Other than Tika Sumpter being quite gorgeous to watch, afraid I have to say there is nothing else redeeming about this- it would have been a mediocre Hallmark Channel Holiday movie.  That all said, I know some people like this sort of thing- I know someone who willingly saw it three times!

Wish I could say better, as again my son is in it and would like for it to be something to be more proud of and perhaps even  lead to greater acting opportunities for him; alas, no.

Bias Alert! I have over 35 Tyler Perry films and plays on dvd and I've seen his plays live twice. But to be honest I was not greatly impressed with this film. Maybe I am suffering a little Tyler Perry burnout. If you are a fan of Larry the Cable Guy and his brand of comedy then you should truly enjoy this film. Madea is always Madea and I personally enjoy all of Tyler's works that he stars in just a little bit more. My complaint with this movie is that some of these people do the dumbest things possible and these dumb actions set the plot for this movie. I don't give spoiler alerts but this film starts by telling us that someone has done something ridiculous, which is followed by a family member doing something else equally as ridiculous and that is where I got stuck. As all of Tyler Perry's works do, this film addresses character flaws and how to correct them. It points out the errors of lying, bullying and spousal abuse and the damage they can cause.
